OBX|1|TX|24532-4^CT Abdomen and Pelvis^LN|1|CLINICAL INDICATION: 69 years old, Abdominal pain||||||F
OBX|2|TX|24532-4^CT Abdomen and Pelvis^LN|2|TECHNIQUE: CT images of the abdomen and pelvis acquired with 90 mL Omnipaque 350 intravenous contrast. CTDI: 12.75 mGy DLP: 651.7 mGy-cm||||||F
OBX|3|TX|24532-4^CT Abdomen and Pelvis^LN|3|COMPARISON: None available.||||||F
OBX|4|FT|24532-4^CT Abdomen and Pelvis^LN|4|FINDINGS: LUNG BASES: Clear.  LIVER: Normal.  GALLBLADDER/BILE DUCTS: Absent gallbladder. The common bile duct measures 1.2 cm in diameter, likely related to previous cholecystectomy.  SPLEEN: There is a large lobulated cystic collection with a few septations within the spleen measuring up to 9.3 x 5.9 x 7.7 cm (series 3, image 18) (series 601, image 67). Smaller irregularly-shaped fluid collections are seen in the spleen superomedially. There is mild fat stranding about the spleen.  PANCREAS: Normal.  ADRENALS: There is an approximately 2.2 x 1.2 cm nodular thickening in the left adrenal gland.  KIDNEYS: There are areas of cortical thinning and scarring in the kidneys bilaterally, with subcentimeter low-density lesions that most likely represent cysts. No suspicious renal mass.  GI TRACT: There is segmental wall thickening of the sigmoid colon with pericolonic fat stranding and inflammatory change in an area of diverticulosis, suggesting diverticulitis.  MESENTERY/LYMPH NODES: No suspicious lymph nodes.  PERITONEUM: No significant free fluid. No free air.  AORTA/VESSELS: Normal abdominal aortic diameter (<3cm). Aortic atherosclerosis.  BLADDER: No significant abnormality.  PELVIC STRUCTURES: No significant abnormality.  SOFT TISSUES: No significant abnormality.  BONES: There is moderate to severe spondylosis at L4-5 and L5-S1. There are degenerative findings in the lower thoracic spine as well. There is multilevel facet arthropathy, worst in the lower lumbar spine.||||||F
OBX|5|TX|24532-4^CT Abdomen and Pelvis^LN|5|IMPRESSION: 1. Sigmoid diverticulitis. Cannot exclude associated contained perforation/abscess or fistula formation. 2. Large lobulated cystic lesion with septations in the spleen, with additional smaller irregular cystic collections and perisplenic fat stranding, concerning for splenic abscess in the appropriate clinical context. Differential includes evolving splenic hematoma/pseudocyst if there is a history of trauma or anticoagulation. 3. Previous cholecystectomy. 4. Nodular thickening of left adrenal gland measures up to 2.2 cm. 5. Other chronic or incidental findings, as above. +||||||F
